# Automated User Migration and Management of AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) Resources 

<figure id="946a" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--h3">
<img
src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*jdK6qaygPGSPH-ajQu82ow.png"
class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*jdK6qaygPGSPH-ajQu82ow.png"
data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-is-featured="true" />
</figure>

**Project description:**

In this project based on a real-world scenario, I acted as Cloud
Specialist with the mission to migrate users in an automated way and
manage AWS IAM (Identity and Access Management) resources.

There were 100 users that needed to be migrated and have MFA
(Multi-factor authentication) enabled on their accounts, as this is a
security best practice.

<figure id="afab" class="graf graf--figure graf-after--p">
<img
src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*AE_ZAX_PBZlbp9eByk9L8g.png"
class="graf-image" data-image-id="1*AE_ZAX_PBZlbp9eByk9L8g.png"
data-width="1920" data-height="1080" />
</figure>

To avoid repetitive and manual tasks in the AWS console, I needed to
think about automating the processes.

Using GitBash with AWS CLI and Shell Script, I was able to seamlessly
migrate all 100 users to AWS, enable MFA to each root user, apply IAM
password policies, and create/attach EnforceMFAPolicy to each group.
This is a crucial skill necessary, for any Cloud Infrastructure
Engineer, to save their client time and money.

